  "prompt": "How thoroughly does steak need to be cooked to kill bacteria?",
  "response": "To ensure that steak is safe to eat and that harmful bacteria such as E. coli and Salmonella are killed, it's important to cook it to the appropriate internal temperature. The USDA recommends that whole cuts of beef, such as steaks, be cooked to a minimum internal temperature of 145\u00b0F (63\u00b0C). \n\nAfter reaching this temperature, it\u2019s advisable to let the steak rest for at least three minutes before cutting or eating it. This resting period allows for the temperature to remain stable or continue to rise slightly, which helps in killing any remaining bacteria.\n\nFor ground beef, which has a higher risk due to bacteria being mixed throughout the meat, the safe cooking temperature is higher at 160\u00b0F (71\u00b0C).\n\nUsing a meat thermometer can help ensure that you achieve these safe temperatures when cooking steak and other meats.",
